<paragraph blockId="4.[212,1173,1183,1527]" pageId="4" pageNumber="603">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Matsumura 1931, p" authorityYear="1054" box="[338,463,1183,1207]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Nippoptilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[338,463,1183,1207]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="603">Nippoptilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially differentiated from its allies by frons not projected forward; labial palpus long and slender; both lobes of forewing liner with distinct termen, except that of 
<emphasis box="[458,632,1247,1271]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="603">
<taxonomicName box="[458,627,1247,1271]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Nippoptilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipedalis">N. cinctipedalis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
three lobes of hindwing linear (
<figureCitation box="[977,1109,1247,1271]" captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="3.[144,221,1071,1093]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,178,1041]" captionTargetId="figure-236@3.[144,1104,177,1041]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figures 1–5. Wing venation of Nippoptilia spp., and Platyptilia spp. (1) Nippoptilia cinctipedalis (Walker). (2) N. distigmata Kim and Byun sp. nov. (3) N. issikii Yano. (4) N. vitis (Sasaki). (5) Platyptilia farfarellus Zeller." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4666791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4666791/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="603">Figures 1–4</figureCitation>
), and a well-developed scale-tooth terminally on the third lobe in hindwing (
<figureCitation box="[1009,1160,1279,1303]" captionStart="Figures 6–13" captionStartId="5.[144,221,1452,1474]" captionTargetBox="[145,1104,189,1420]" captionTargetId="figure-127@5.[144,1104,173,1420]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 6–13. Adults of Nippoptilia spp. (6) Nippoptilia cinctipedalis (Walker). (7) ditto, wing pattern. (8) N. distigmata Kim and Byun sp. nov. (9) ditto, wing pattern. (10) N. issikii Yano. (11) ditto, wing pattern. (12) N. vitis (Sasaki). (13) ditto, wing pattern." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4666793" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4666793/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="603">Figures 6–13</figureCitation>
). The male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[438,600,1311,1335]" captionStart="Figures 14–23" captionStartId="6.[212,289,1140,1162]" captionTargetBox="[219,1172,173,1105]" captionTargetId="figure-318@6.[212,1172,173,1109]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 14–23. Male genitalia of Nippoptilia spp. (14) Nippoptilia cinctipedalis (Walker). (15) ditto, aedeagus. (16) N. distigmata Kim and Byun sp. nov. (17) ditto, aedeagus. (18) ditto, juxta. (19) N. issikii Yano. (20) ditto, aedeagus. (21) ditto, juxta. (22) N. vitis (Sasaki). (23) ditto, aedeagus. Scale bar: 0.5mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4666795" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4666795/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="603">Figures 14–23</figureCitation>
) are well defined by the symmetric elongate valvae, sometimes with separated sacculus; tegumen deeply incised medially dividing two large plates with rounded apex. The female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[723,875,1375,1399]" captionStart="Figures 24–30" captionStartId="7.[144,221,1287,1309]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,177,1256]" captionTargetId="figure-228@7.[144,1104,172,1256]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figures 24–30. Female genitalia of Nippoptilia spp. (24) Nippoptilia cinctipedalis (Walker). (25) N. distigmata Kim and Byun sp. nov. (26) ditto, antrum. (27) N. issikii Yano. (28) ditto, antrum. (29) N. vitis (Sasaki). (30) ditto, antrum. Scale bar: 0.5mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4666797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4666797/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="603">Figures 24–30</figureCitation>
) have extremely long apophyses posteriores; mostly without Apophysis anterioris except 
<taxonomicName authority="(Walker)" baseAuthorityName="Walker" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Nippoptilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinctipedalis">
<emphasis box="[911,1172,1408,1432]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="603">Nippoptilia cinctipedalis</emphasis>
(Walker)
</taxonomicName>
; papillae analis with sharply pointed caudal lobes; antrum generally sclerotized, long, tube-like, or cup-shaped, with numerous coiled hairs laterally; corpus bursae usually with a pair of leaf-shaped signa.
</paragraph>
